first ethnography of its kind, Weighing the Future examines the sociopolitical implications of ongoing pregnancy trials in the United States and the United Kingdom, illuminating how processes of scientific knowledge production are linked to capitalism, surveillance, and environmental reproduction. The environments we imagine to shape our genes, bodies, and future health are tied to race, gender, and structures of inequality. This groundbreaking book makes the case that science, and how we translate it, is a reproductive project that requires feminist vigilance. Instead of fixating on a future at risk, this book brings attention to the present at stake.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aClinical trialsxPolitical aspectszGreat Britain. 0aClinical trialsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aClinical trialsxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aClinical trialsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEpigeneticszGreat Britain. 0aEpigeneticszUnited States. 0aHuman reproductionxEnvironmental aspectszGreat Britain. 0aHuman reproductionxEnvironmental aspectszUnited States. 0aPregnant womenzGreat BritainxCase studies. 0aPregnant womenzUnited StatesxCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107391520 cprintz978052038013440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520380158?locatt=m